data.title: The Simpsons: Real location of Springfield revealed by creator Matt Groening
data.meta_description: Simpsons creator Matt Groening finally revealed the location of Springfield - it's based on the town in Oregon, near Portland, where he grew up.
data.text:
Revealed after 23 seasons: The REAL Springfield as Matt Groening names town that inspired The Simpsons' home

It's the town that inspired the much-loved fictional town of Springfield, but this one has 41 - not five - Simpsons living in it.

After 23 seasons of tantalising secrets, Simpsons creator Matt Groening finally revealed that the town of Springfield, Oregon, was the inspiration for the show's setting.

Homer, Marge, and the rest of the Simpsons clan have lived for the entirety of the show on Evergreen Terrace - incidentally, at the same address of Mr Groening's childhood home in Portland.

D'oh! After 23 seasons, Simpsons creator Matt Groening finally confirmed that the Springfield in his show is based off of a town of the same name in Oregon

Mr Groening told the magazine that he was inspired by the television show Father Knows Best, which took place in a place called Springfield.

Common moniker: Creator Matt Groening said that he let his audience think that Springfield could be anywhere

Pop culture history: The town of Springfield was incorporated in 1885, nearly a century before the popular show was created

Springfield, Oregon, is 100 miles south of Mr Groening's hometown of Portland, and has a population of 59,000 as of the 2010 census.

Mr Groening said he has long given fake answers when asked about the Simpsons' hometown.

He told the magazine it was because ‘I don’t want to ruin it for people, you know?

‘Whenever people say it’s Springfield, Ohio, or Springfield, Massachusetts, or Springfield, wherever, I always go, “Yep, that’s right.”’

The animated comedy, which has been on air a staggering 23 years, has made a running joke about Springfield’s vague location, dangling false clues in front of fans, only to contradict its information in later episodes.

Mum's the word: Matt Groening, seen posing with a life-sized Bart and Homer, was famously evasive about the real location of Springfield for more than two decades

Lacking: One thing the real town of Springfield doesn't have? A nuclear plant

In one episode, daughter and saxophone prodigy Lisa points to Springfield on a map, but the animated ‘camera view’ is blocked by son Bart's head.

In the interview, Mr Groening said that he took living in Portland – on Evergreen Terrace, no less – for granted.

He said that the only reason he’s lived in Los Angeles for so long is because of his significant involvement with the entertainment industry.

‘Everything you can experience in Los Angeles, you can have a much better version of it in Portland- including, very basically, the air you breathe.’

The series has been on the air for 22 years, becoming the longest-running American sitcom, the longest-running American animated program and a cultural phenomenon, with colleges devoting courses to studying it.

People in the real Springfield - the one in Oregon - took on the mantle of the show's hometown after Mr Groening visited before the release of the The Simpsons Movie in 2007.

Small town: Kwik-E-Mart is one of the mainstays of the show

The real deal: Springfield, Oregon, is about 100 miles outside of Portland, Matt Groening's home town

Back then, tiny Springfield, Vermont, beat out 13 other like-named cities, including the one in Oregon, to host the movie premiere. The cities submitted videos meant to connect themselves to the fictional Springfield.

When Springfield, Oregon, community-relations manager Niel Laudati was told about Mr Groening's announcement, he said: 'Oh OK, we knew that.'

The city has already incorporated the Simpsons into its own town lore.

For instance, the Springfield Museum features a couch similar to the animated one shown in the show's opening credits, and a plaque marking the movie's release.

Drink at Moe's: Moe's Tavern is the local watering hole for Homer and the gang, where they spend many a night putting back Duffy beers

Watering hole: Springfield locals head to Jim's Landing on Main St.

'Yo to Springfield, Oregon - the real Springfield!' Mr Groening wrote. 'Your pal, Matt Groening proud Oregonian!'

The Springfield depicted in The Simpsons isn't always a flattering portrait.

The school is falling apart, there's a constant fire at the town dump, and Mayor Quimby is chronically, helplessly corrupt. Not to mention, the nuclear plant with sub-par safety standards.

'We kind of got past it,' Mr Laudati told the Associated Press. 'We don't dwell on the bad stuff. Obviously we don't have a nuclear power plant. We don't have a lot of stuff in the Simpsons.

'What we do have are a lot of blue-collar working families that go to church every week and eat dinner together,' Mr Laudati said. 'That is accurate.'

Go nuts for donuts: Lard Lad is a parody of the Big Boy chain restaurants

Hole in one: Actual Springfield locals get their sugar fixes at Master Donuts

The Simpson family are named after Mr Groening's family -- father Homer (named after the Greek poet of the same name), mother Marge, and sisters Lisa and Maggie.

Bart is based on the creator himself, although Mr Groening changed the name from 'Matt' to 'Bart' because he 'had this idea of an angry father yelling 'Bart.'

He told the magazine that Bart sounded kind of like bark—like a barking dog, and he thought it would sound funny.

The inspirations drawn from Oregon didn't just stop at the town name.

Mr Groening also said he named some of the characters after streets in Portland, including Reverend Lovejoy, the school bully Kearney and the Simpsons' annoyingly loveable neighbour Ned Flanders.

Even the address that America's favourite animated family live at, 632 Evergreen Terrace, is named after Mr Groening's own childhood home address.

Personal touch: Debra Gruell, Executive Director Springfield Museum, holds a plaque that was given by Matt Groening to the museum

Revealing: The plaque reads: 'Yo to Springfield, Oregon - the REAL Springfield! Your pal, Matt Groening, proud Oregonian'

Sofa, so good: Ms Gruell cozies on the couch with the Simpsons clan

Not only that, but there are 41 'Simpsons' registered in the town limits. While there is no Homer Simpson, there is a Harold.

The Simpsons was created by Mr Groening for Fox television and first aired in 1989.

It is the longest-running American sitcom in history, broadcast in more than 100 countries and 50 languages, and it still attracts an average 7.7million U.S. viewers weekly.

The show has witnessed incredible talent throughout its near quarter-century on television.

Conan O’Brien served as a writer and producer for the show in the early 1990s, and has featured the voice talents of everyone from Steve Buscemi, Stephen Hawking, Glenn Close, Julia Louis-Dreyfus, to Simon Cowell.

In the sixth season of South Park, blundering fourth-grader Butters’ alter ego Professor Chaos comes up with a series of plans to take over the world, only to find that those plots have already been exhausted by the Simpsons.

The episode gave a flagrant wink to the long-running sitcom, with the familiar refrain of ‘the Simpsons already did it’ after nearly every suggested plot point in South Park.
